column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shippers location to Clean Harbor’s in transit storage location in Bristol CT for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities of hazardous waste for continuing transportation to the intended waste management facility. While transferring one container in Bristol the forlift being used for the drum transfer punctured the drum causing the spill within containment. Response personnel cleaned up spillage donning the proper PPE and placed the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris. The container was secured and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility. All required local fire dept and state DEP reports were made.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed by the driver. The drum was damaged due to the forklift puncturing the drum. In order to prevent a recurrence, the plant forklift operator was spoken with and is being retrained regarding the importance of safe forklift operation and preventing these type of incidences from reoccuring.

column168: Today we came across a CLC "Customer Loaded Container" under awb. 001-BOS-17144956  (PER SEAFOOD) that traveled from BOS to JFK in hub truck, Then flew on board AA443/04 JFK to MIA and its final destination is SDQ booked for AA1481/05. When it arrived here in MIA our FSC inspected the condition of the ULD "Unit Load Device" and it was found to be unserviceable. This placed us in a position in which we had to change the ULD in order to expedite the shipment. So we had to rebuilt this ULD. When we were in the process of rebuilding this shipment of Seafood,  we found two (2) boxes containing six (6) aerosol cans with a net weight of 12 oz. (340g) of the product “Bakers Joy” Baking Spray with flour ( http://www.bakersjoy.com/ ) hidden between the Styrofoam Seafood Boxes. These boxes inside this CLC’s also contained the CCSF Cargo Stamp. This was a clear trigger for a Hidden DG and possibly a Hidden DG scenario for a Class 3 Aerosol Flammable. No MSDS found for this product.  Inccident was reported to the FAA and we were instructed to fill 5800. Inccident still under investigation.
column169: We are now questioning the Shipper who loaded and tendered this shipment into our ULD. This shipper has a CCSF security Screening Certificate for the TSA and is obligated to report to us the actual content of the cargo. Incident is currently under investigation. We have now removed the aerosol boxes away from the seafood and placed it in our DG area for FAA further investigation.

column168: Driver entered trailer and forklift blade punctured drum causing initial damage.  Approximately 55 gallons of material released to the trailer floor and the ground below.  Facility employees in defensive position, applied sawdust to the liquid in order to keep the material from going down a nearby drain.  Supervisor contacted Con-way Freight Safety Department at 0124.  ERTS contacted by Safety to coordinate the emergency response clean up.  Terra Contracting contacted by ERTS.  Terra on-site at 0620.  Terra stated to have neutralized impacted area and applied granular absorbents to collect the liquid.  Per ERTS, Terra applied sodium bicarbonate solution and 9 bags of Oil-Dri.  Departed scene at 1054. At 1324 salvage drum containing material explodes.  Chemical reaction with materials used in clean up activity created build up of heat and pressure inside of drum.  Facility is evacuated. 9-1-1 notified.  Safety Manager notified.  Multiple fire departments (F/D) respond including Fremont and Angola. F/D point of contact - Fire Chief Eric Hufnagle.  F/D sprays down drums as necessary to keep cool until Terra returns to site. Approximately 1630, Chief Hufnagle closes North Old 27 as a precautionary measure following ERG recommendations and the amount of hazardous materials in close proximity to reactive drum(s) including propane tanks.  Two outlet malls within the recommended isolation distance and a hotel were evacuated.  One dockworker close to the explosion, decontaminated (washed down with water) and transported to hospital as a precautionary measure.  Material continues to react until neutralized.  Road and businesses re-opened 1820 after material neutralized. Approximately 1910 dockworker released from hospital no injuries noted.  NRC and IDEM notified by both ERTS and Con-way Freight.  04/06/2013 decisions made to stage drums of material outdoors and continue monitoring temperature.  04/07/2013 contractor diluting material with sand per Dow recommendation. NRC report numbers 1043080 and 1043081.
column169: Initial Incident root casue: Forklift mishanding   Corrective action: Forklift retaining completed. Share lessons learned with field.  Additiona gap discovered: Emergency response number not called immediately.  Corrective action - Process change. Safety Department to make initial contact in future. Change to be documented in internal policy and communicated to field supervisors.  Additional gap discovered: Improper materials used during mitigation and cleanup placed within sealed recovery drum.   Corrective action - Address issues with terra Contracting ERTS.

column168: On April 1, 2013 at approximately 1807 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Richmond AACA Yard discovered UTLX 211070, a loaded tank car of Alcohols NOS leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, RPMG LLC, Kevin Brim, 515-835-11345, was notified via CHEMTREC report # 2013040100173. Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the manway cover gasket was the wrong size and the manway swing bolts were less than tool tight. The manway was secured with an intact shipper seal. Hepaco personnel replaced the gasket and secured the tank car for transportation.    This incident did not require a special switching move.  This incident does not require a 7.1    Cause Code=208  NARRI: 5(5+3+0)x(2+0)=80

column168: USPS AMC SFO TENDERED 47 PIECES OF CIVIL AIRMAIL FOR UPLIFT ON FLIGHT KZ109/03APR13 WITH AN OFFLOAD POINT OF NARITA, JAPAN TO BE DELIVERED TO THE JAPAN POST. PER HANDLING BY THE AIRLINE, NIPPON CARGO AIRLINES, BEFORE LOADING ONTO AN AIRLINE ULD, 1 PIECE OF 47 WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE A LITHIUM ION BATTERY LABEL ON THE SIDE OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX. THIS MAIL PIECE IS IDENTIFIED WITH USPS RECEPTACLE NUMBER USSFOAJPTYOAACN30799005900046 AT 4.6 KILOGRAMS WITH A DESTINATION OF TOKYO INTL JAPAN POST. PER THE DISCOVERY OF THIS LITHIUM ION BATTERY LABEL, THE PIECE WAS SEPARATED AND HELD FOR RETURN TO THE USPS.    THIS MAIL PIECE WAS NOT MOVED ON KZ109/03APR13, HOWEVER RETURNED TO USPS AMC SFO ON 03APR13. PLEASE BE ADVISED NO INCIDENT.
column169: CONTINUE TO VERIFY EACH PIECE OF MAIL TENDERED BY THE USPS AND REJECT TRANSPORT TO DESTINATION IF AND WHEN DANGEROUS GOODS LABELS OR ANY SIGN OF DANGEROUS GOODS ARE IDENTIFIED ON ANY PIECE.

column168: On April 9, 2013, a SOCI Petroleum tanker overfilled an above ground storage tank at the aforementioned location resulting in the release of approximately 75 gallons of diesel fuel to the containment pit and AST walls. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site and the released diesel in the containment unit was pumped out and containerized. The AST walls were then pressure washed and the liquid generated was pumped to the onsite oil/water separator unit.

column168: On April 12, 2013, United States Environmental Services responded to the site and discovered approximately 3 gallons of UN1760 product released in an empty trailer. USES personnel neutralized the impacted area and pH tested it to confirm neutralization. No information could be provided regarding the suspected cause of the release or the fate of the cargo. It was reported that a mechanic was treated onsite for burns he sustained while working on or near the impacted trailer. It was reported that his hands were flushed with water.

On April 16, 2013, an R&L Carriers trailer experienced a punctured tote of UN3082 at the aforementioned location. It was reported that personnel drilled into the tote while placarding the trailer. The hole in the tote was plugged by facility personnel. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site and transferred the material from the damaged tote into a new tote. Absorbents were applied to the impacted trailer floor and worked in thoroughly. All impacted absorbents and PPE were containerized for transportation and disposal.

column168: On 04/10/2013, at 1112 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Mobile, AL Siebert yard, discovered SANX 30000, a loaded tank car of Hazardous Waste Liquid N.O.S., Tetrachloroethylene, leaking from the manway. The car was isolated and the NRC, shipper , Alabama DEM and CHEMTREC report #2013-04-10-00138 were notified.  USES (United States Environmental Services), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the manway bolts were not secured. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Joe Licari, 312-898-7983. Contractor personnel secured the manway, decontaminated the car and cleaned up the spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.  A 7.1 report is not required.    Cause Code:200  NARRI:5(5+1+1)X(3+0) = 105

column168: A Trimac tractor tanker was involved in an apparent roll over incident in which an estimated 1 gallon of UN2218 Acrylic Acid was released to the pavement and adjacent soils along with an estimated 5 gallons of diesel fuel and engine fluids. The contractor transferred the rolled over tanker into a replacement tanker. They then neutralized the released acid, applied absorbents to the impacted areas, worked the absorbents in and swept the impacted areas clean. They then hand excavated the impacted  soils. All waste was containerized and transported off site for pending disposal.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While hooking up the unloading line, the Wayne Transport, Inc. driver accidentally connected to the incorrect product line and began unloading the product.  The free product was discharged onto the floor inside of the facility.  Approximately 7 gallons of free product were released.  Hawkins, Inc. personnel donned SCBA and CPC for the initial response.  Ammonia levels were measured at 70ppm and respiratory protection was downgraded to air purifying respirator.  The free liquid was directed into a trench and ultimately a sump pit, where the product was neutralized in place.  No injuries or exposures were reported.

column168: ON FEBRUARY 28, 2013 A SHIPMENT OF SPENT CARBON FROM THE ABOVE REFERENCED SHIPPER/OFFEROR WAS RECEIVED BY THE CALGON CARBON CORPORATION (CALGON) BIG SANDY PLANT IN CATTLETTSBURG, KY. AT THE TIME OF ARRIVAL THE SHIPMENT WAS EXPECTED TO BE NON-HAZARDOUS BASED ON A PRE-APPROVED 2010 WASTE PROFILE AND THE BILL OF LADING SHIPPING DOCUMENTS. THROUGH RANDOM SPOT CHECKING OF SHIPMENTS RECEIVED AT THE FACILITY, A SAMPLE OF THE WASTE HAD BEEN COLLECTED AND FORWARDED TO CALGON'S CARBON ACCEPTANCE DEPARTMENT LOCATED IN PITTSBURGH, PA FOR EVALUATION. THE SAMPLE WAS TESTED FOR TCLP VOLATILES BY TEST AMERICA ON OR AFTER 03/19/2013. UPON REVIEW OF THE FINAL TEST REPORT ON 04/08/2013, IT WAS DETERMINED THE SPENT CARBON SHIPMENT SHOULD HAVE BEEN CHARACTERIZED AS RCRA-HAZARDOUS FOR VINYL CHLORIDE AND MANIFESTED WITH THE D043 WAST CODE. THE SHIPPER/OFFEROR DID NOT PROVIDE THE REQUIRED MANIFEST FOR THIS SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS TRANSPORTED BY DART. TRUCKING COMPANY WHO IS LICENSED TO TRANSPORT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.
column169: The waste generator has been notified by Calgon that the characterization of the spent carbon received at the Catlettsburg facility no longer matches the pre-approved waste profile; and therefore, no further shipments will be accepted by the facility until a new waste characterization is completed and approved by Calgon.

column168: At 16:58 it was reported that tank car PLCX 224373, a load of Chlorobutane Butyl Acetate, was leaking from the B-end above the trucks at the KCS Knoche Yard in  Kansas City.     The lading was transferred from PLCX 224373 to intermodal tanks and delivered to destination. This tank car has been cleaned + purged of all hazmat residue. The shipper has been placed on notice that this car cannot proceed to home shop on its own wheels.     *Two KCS employees indicated they detected odor of material, claimed exposure, and elected to be examined at North Kansas City Hospital.  Employee #1 reported trouble breathing, light headedness, and burning eyes.  Employee #2 was taken to the same hospital for minor throat irritation.  Both employees were thouroughly examined and released back into work as of Monday April 8, 2013 at 1300 hrs.    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released. It has been reported by the shipper/consignee that 1,336 gallons total had been released, of that, 40 gallons had been released in the KCS Kansas City Knoche Yard. The remainder was released from points in between offeror and points of incident.    File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:  The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence.

column168: On 04/18/2013, at 01:51 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Taft Yard discovered AGLX 1121, a loaded  tank car of Petroleum Gases, Liquefied, leaking from the vapor line valve. The car was isolated and the shipper, Enterprise Products Operating, local fire department, NRC, Florida State Watch Office and CHEMTREC report #2013-04-18-00021 were notified. SWS Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor line valve secondary containment plug less than tool tight and the vapor line valve slightly open. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Helen Johnnes at 281-797-4309. Contractor personnel closed the valve and secured the secondary containment plug. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.    Cause Code:136  NARRI:5(5+5+0) x (2+4) = 300

column168: During preparation for unloading at the fuel track in the railyard, tank car DBUX 300329 was observed dripping commodity from its bottom tank area near the A-end stub sill. column168: TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE TRAVELING SOUTH ON HIGHWAY I-37 FEEDER ROAD. THE UNIT WAS TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY 55 MPH WHEN IT APPROACHED A 40 MPH "S" CURVE. THE UNIT WAS TRAVELING AT A SPEED THAT THE DRIVER COULD NOT CONTROL WHILE IN THE CURVE. THE DRIVER THEN ATTEMPTED TO CORRECT AND FAILED CAUSING THE UNIT TO ROLL OVER LEAVING THE ROADWAY. THE CARGO TANK STRUCK THE ROADWAY EDGE CAUSING THE TANK/TRAILER TO RUPTURE. THIS CAUSED A 4 IN HOLE IN THE TRAILER WHICH RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 150 BARRELS OF CONDENSATE/PETROLEUM. THIRD PARTY EMERGENCY RESPONSE/CLEAN UP TEAM WAS DISPATCHED AND ARRIVED WITHIN 20 MINUTES OF THE ACCIDENT. EMERGENCY ACTION PLAN WAS INITIATED AND WORK WITHOUT FLAW. AREA HAS BEEN COMPLETLEY REMEDIATED.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: UPRR notified BNSF that an entrained tank car in a BNSF train operating on UPRR tracks was dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV). The BNSF train was stopped and entrained tank car ETCX 21144 was identified as dripping residue commodity from its bottom outlet auxiliary valve. Contract responders inspected ETCX 21144 observing several drips per minute from the bottom outlet. Responders reported finding the primary bottom outlet valve's operating handle in a partial open position and not pinned. The auxiliary bottom outlet valve was also in an open position with its closure plug not tool tight. Responders closed both valves and tool tightened the loose closure plug which ended any further commodity drips. New seals numbered 85883 and 85884 were applied at the pinned valve handles. Responders applied soda ash to neutralize ground spillage observed under ETCX 21144. Response was concluded by 1830 hrs. CDT, 4/05/2013.   The side stencil on ETCX 21144 indicated that it was last qualified in year 2003 and due in 2013.

column168: Leak from the bottom of tank car SHPX207021 was reported by the car department in Roseville CA.  Roseville Fire was notified and responding as well as UP Hazmat manager.    A Level A entry was performed and the leak from the bottom of the car was stopped by placing a wooden plug in a hole that was approximately the size of a dime.  The duration of the leak was unknown, but from the time reported to the time it was stopped was approximately 2 hours.      The rail car could not be moved so a transfer of product was conducted and completed without incident and the car was then transported to a separate track for further investigation and till the shipper could make repairs.

column163: BLDG. 53 ENT S-1, DEN. FED. CTR, MS-974
column168: WE ARE THE RECIPIENT OF A UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENT, THE EVENTS DESCRIBED ARE AS WE HAVE COME TO UNDERSTAND THEM. THE PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED BY TRACERCO IN AUSTRALIA TO DENVER CO. TRACERCO LABELED AND TRANSPORTED THE PACKAGE CORRECTLY BY AIR WITH SINGAPORE AIRLINES INTO LOS ANGELES, CA. IN LOS ANGELES, CA COMET-EXPORTAIR, INC. TOOK POSSESSION OF THE PACKAGE AND RE-PACKAGED IT INTO A FIBERBOARD BOX AND THEN AGAIN INTO ANOTHER FIBERBOARD BOX. NEITHER BOX HAD APPROPRIATE LABELING OR MARKING. THE BOX AS THEN DROPPED OFF WITH LAND AIR EXPRESS IN LOS ANGELES, CA AND LAND AIR EXPRESS TRUCKED THE SHIPMENT TO DENIVER, CO. THE PACKAGE ARRIVED AT THE SORING FACILITY FOR THE DENVER FEDERAL CENTER (DFC) IN DENVER, CO ON THE MORNING OF 4-15-13. SHIPPING PERSONNEL SORTED AND DELIVERED THE PACKAGE TO ITS FINAL RECIPIENT, TIM DEBEY. WHEN THE PACKAGE WAS DELIVERED TO TIM DEBEY IT WAS DISCOVERED THE PACKAGE WAS RADIOACTIVE DUE TO NEARBY RADIATION ALARMS SOUNDING. TIM AND STAFF WERE EXPECTING A SHIPMENT OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL. TIM AND STAFF OPENED THE BOX AND DISCOVERED THE SHIPMENT WAS THE MATERIAL THEY HAD BEEN WAITING FOR BUT IT WAS ALSO AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENT. THE RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL WAS STILL CONTAINED WITHIN IT'S APPROPRIATE TYPE A CONTAINER WHICH WAS CORRECTLY LABELED INSIDE THE TWO FIBERBOARD BOXES. HOWEVER, THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOXES HAD NO LABELS, NO MARKINGS, AND NO ASSOCIATED DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPPING PAPERS. THE RECIPIENT PERFORMED A RADIOACTIVE SHIPMENT RECEIPT SURVEY AS REQUIRED PER 10 CFR 20 AND FOUND THE SHIPMENT TO BE HAVE ACCEPTABLE CONTAMINATION AND RADIATION DOSE LEVELS PER 10 CFR 20.
column169: AS THE RECIPIENT WE HAVE NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, TRACERCO. TRACERCO IS CONDUCTING AN INTERNAL INVESTIGATION AND DOES NOT PLAN TO UTILIZE THE SERVICES OF COMET-EXPORTAIR, INC. AGAIN.

column168: This railcar was observed leaking by an FRA Hazmat Inspector, Angela Kellum, during a yard audit.  All appropriate departments notified.  The railcar was isolated.  Upon closer inspection, product was observed coming from below the manway cover.  The manway was secured by seal # 9630429.  The bolts were checked for tightness.  Several of the bolts were found to be loose.  The bolts were tightened and the leak was secured. The railcar was released to destination.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: One cylinder last containing UN2363 was believed to be empty. During shipment the pressure relief valve ruptured and released UN2363 into the air. The driver contacted local 911 coordinate a response to the release. Local 911 dispatched local police and a Conocophillips HazMat Team. ERS of OK also responded to the site. The Conocophillips HazMat team and ERS personnel ventilated the vehicle and then placed a wooden plus in the damaged relief valve and resecured the cylinder within the vehicle. The shipment was then taken to the nearest R&L Carriers Terminal.
column169: This is considered a one time incident.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: Tank car NATX 300757 was reported dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area during an inbound BNSF train inspection in the railyard. Contract responders placed a catch receptacle under NATX 300757 and inspected the closed BOV. The commodity drip source was at the BOV mounting flange area. Responders attempted to stop the drips by tightening the BOV mounting flange bolts which did not stop the dripping. Responders then applied putty material around the flange connection to seal off the drips. The BOV mounting flange gasket was suspected as the leak cause. Spillage evaporated as no ground staining or commodity smell was noted.  NATX 300757 was carefully moved to the facility's containment area/pit for product transfer. On 4/06/2013, all commodity within NATX 300757 was transferred to another suitable tank car without further incident. The drip pit was cleaned of all liquids which consisted primarily of rainwater from a previous rain event. OTMA FRA-13040270 was received to transport NATX 300757 to a qualified repair facility.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column169: The company has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn.  After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate. Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: Tank car ACFX 94995 in the railyard was reported leaking commodity from its top fitting area with no significant ground impact observed. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected ACFX 94995 finding the leak source at the liquid eduction line's closure cap that was loose. The responder tool tightened the loose closure cap (4 full turns) which ended any further commodity release. Baking soda was applied to neutralize all observed spillage at the valve housing area, top side shell and ground impact areas.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: During switching operations the crew noticed leak and odor from around manway area of UTLX 212283.  Car was isolated and an environmental contractor called to investigate.  Contractor found the manway gasket was cracked.  Gasket was replaced, manway bolts tightened, and car returned to transportation.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: While performing a routine mechanical inspection, a carman noticed an odor coming from tank car GATX 60252.  An NS environmental contractor was called and metered the car for H2S.  Readings were zero at the fittings on top but they got reading from 40 to 330ppm from the bottom of the car, around the bottom outlet area.  Bottom outlet cap was "snooped" and found to be not properly secured.  Cap was removed, gasket examined (found to be OK) and the cap reapplied.  No further leaks were found with "snoop" but odor persisted.  H2S readings from 40 - 330ppm were detected coming from the annular space between the jacket and the tank.  Shipper's contractor checked the car and determined that the odor was from product spilled between the jacket and the tank and there were no further leaks.  Car was released back into transporation on shipper's recommendation.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Several unmarked fibreboard cartons were discovered to contain undeclared Lithium Ion Batteries Packed with Equipment (UN 3481). Shipment was tendered and booked on a passenger flight. Upon discovery, the shipment was secured and segregated. E-mails were sent to the local field office of the FAA. On Monday, an agent from FAA (Steven J. Redeker) came to the facility and inspected the shipment. He subsequently made contact with the freight forwarder (Pilot Air Freight) and the Shipper (AMG Technologies). Currently, the shipment Is still on "HOLD" awaiting more information from the shipper and a release from the FAA.
column169: Shippers and their agents (freight forwarders) must review all documents and be aware of the potential hazards associated with the goods they describe. What may be common house hold commodities could, in fact, be harmful or become harmful during the transportation chain. We have seen how Lithium batteries pose a substantial threat to safety in recent years. By now, it should be common knowledge that what powers a computer runs the risk of overheating or even spontaneous combustion.

column168: The driver reported that a customer rep was assisting with the transfer of product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank. As it neared the end the rep went to come around the tank and signal to shut down and by that point 10-15 gallons had overflowed into a containment area.  Customer used a vac trailer to clean it out of the containment area.

column168: Employee reported that there was a corrosive spill which had occured on trailer PAMT-130255 at 07:50 on 2APR2013. Supervisor went to investigate the issue and found spillage of corrosive material to be present. The small box containing 5liters of R2 Plus Hygienic Hard Surface Cleaner (Corrosive 8 PGII, UN1903), was found crushed between the PLT it was initially shipped on and another PLT. No blocking or bracing appeared to have been used as a preventative precaution which would have avoided the incident. One driver, also noted that the PAMT driver broke hard which caused shifting of the contents of the trailer. Nevertheless, the loader, would ultimately be the responsible party. Duration of the release was most likely very quick, a matter of minutes perhaps.  Cleaned up in-house on discovery.

Driver opened the trailer at interim terminal and saw the product on the floor. He could also smell the product. He called his supervisor over to show him the damage. A copy of the B/L was obtained and a copy of the Haz Mat guide page for the product. The SCM was brought out to check and determined if the trailer could be unloaded safely. The product was unloaded onto the dock onto cardboard. Oil Dry was put down into the spilled product. and the trailer was unloaded. All shrinkwrap that had the spilled product was removed and the shipment was rewrapped. The shipment that caused the leak was a 330 gal tote that had a 2" to 3" crack on the corner. The product was spilling from the XCW terminal to XRF terminal, confined to trailer floor. Looks like there was about 5 gals or less lost. Damage product was placed back on the trailer to isolate with cardboard under it until it could be transferred into another tote by vendor.

column168: On April 10th at 1820 hours, personnel in the CSXT Hoskins Road Transflo Facility discovered TILX 280684, a loaded tank car of Acetone leaking from top of car. The car was isolated and shipper, Haverhill Chemicals was notified via CHEMTREC report number 2013-0410-00255.  A CSXT hazardous materials manager, was dispatched to the scene and found product being released out of the pressure relief device valve.  Hazardous Material Manager was able to reduce the pressure on the tank car by slightly opening the vapor line valve.  Liquid was observed being released from the valve during this operation indicating that the container was overloaded.  The issue identified and required corrective actions were communicated to Haverhills representative John Brooks at 740-550-4803.  On April 11th, CSXTs Transflo + HEPACO employees off loaded 1985 gallons of product into UTLX 201934.  This incident did not require a special switching move. No 7.1 required.    Cause Code:  419   NARRI: 5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80
column169: Ensure operators follow standard operating procedures to avoid overloading tank cars.

column168: On April 14, 2013 at 1655 hours, personnel in the CSXT Hamlet Yard discovered NTLX 1072, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., dripping liquid from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Westway Terminal Company, was contacted via Chemtel - report number 2013-1145.  HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the cause of the release was due to two of four liquid line mounting flange bolts/nuts being less than tool tight.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to shipper representative, Craig Patakay at 215-298-3541. Contractor personnel properly secured the loose valve and decontaminated the car.  The leak was secured and the car was released to destination.  This incident did not require a special switching move. No 7.1 required.    Cause Code: 270   NARRI: 5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60

column168: On 04/15/2013 at 17:32 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Rice Yard, Waycross Georgia, discovered UTLX 661043, a residue tank car of Elevated Temperature Liquid, N.O.S. Petroleum Asphalt, leaking from the bottom outlet valve. The car was isolated and the shipper Ergon Inc, NRC and CHEMTREC report #2013-04-15-00194 were notified. A CSXT General Car Foreman was dispatched to the scene and found the bottom outlet valve cap off, the bottom outlet valve handle was not secured in the closed position and all eight manway securement bolts in the down position. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Georgia Bidwell at 229-248-0804. The bottom outlet cap was secured, the valve was closed and the manway securement bolts were secured. The car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. The car was isolated and the shipper, International Paper, Alabama EMA, NRC and Chemtrec- report 2013-04-22-00055, were notified. column168: On April 22, 2013 at 14:19 hours, personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard discovered TCBX 230118, a loaded tank car of Environmentally Hazardous Substances, Liquid, N.O.S. leaking from around the manway. The car was isolated and the shipper, Sasol North America, was notified via CHEMTREC Report  2013-04-22-00153. column168: THE AFFECTED PACKAGE WAS DROPPED OFF IN THE OFFICE USED BY THE UPS ACCEPTANCE AUDITOR. THE ACCEPTANCE AUDITOR SELECTED THE PACKAGE AND PUT ON IT ON THE FLOOR, AT WHICH TIME THE BOTTOM OF THE INNER BOTTLE CRACKED OFF OF THE BODY. THE CONTENTS PROCEEDED TO SATURATE THE BOX, RELEASING AN OVERWHELMING ODOR. THE AUDTIOR NOTIFIED A RESPONSIBLE SUPERVISOR OF THE SPILL AND ASSOCIATED ODOR. THE SUPERVISOR CALLED A UPS DESIGNATED RESPONDER, WHO MADE THE DETERMINATION THAT AN OUTSIDE RESPONDER WAS NEEDED TO CLEAN UP THE  SPILL. AT THIS TIME THE FACILITY WAS EVACUATED. SUBSEQUENT EVALUATION OF THE PACKAGE SUGGESTS THAT WHILE A FORM-FITTING CUSHIONING COMPONENT WAS PRESENT ON THE TOP OF THE BOTTLE, ONLY KRAFT PAPER HAD BEEN USED FOR PADDING AT THE BOTTOM, POSSIBLY EXPOSING THE BOTTLE TO UNDUE SHOCK. THE RELEASED MATERIAL DESTROYED MANY OF THE PACKAGE MARKINGS, INCLUDING THE SPECIFICATION MARKING AND DESTINATION ADDRESS.
column169: BUSINESS DEVELOPMENT WAS ADVISED THAT INNER PACKAGING SHOULD BE INCREASED TO PREVENT FUTURE ISSUES WITH SIMILAR PRODUCTS. BUSINESS DEVELOPMENT COMMUNICATED ADVICE TO VWR.

column168: AT THE CUSTOMER'S PRODUCT UNLOADING POINT, THERE IS A VERTICAL DRAIN PIPING SYSTEM THAT IS USED TO DRAIN ANY REMAINING RESIDUAL PRODUCT ONCE THE UNLOADING PROCESS HAS BEEN COMPLETED. A 3" BALL VALVE AT THE TOP OF THE VERTICAL LINE WHERE IT 'T'S' INTO THE UNLOADING (RECEIVING) LINE IS OPENED TO DRAIN THE UNLOADING LINE AGAIN, ONCE THE UNLOADING PROCESS HAS BEEN COMPLETED. THE DRIVER OBSERVED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE DRAIN LINE INTO THE CONTAINMENT BASIN BELOW AND THEN APPROXIMATELY 20 MINUTES AFTER HE STARTED UNLOADING THE TANKER, THE DRIP CHANGED TO A SLOW BUT CONTINUOUS FLOW. PLANT PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED AND AFTER ANOTHER 10 MINUTES HAD GONE BY AND ATTEMPTS TO REPAIRE THE LEAKING VALVE PROVED TO BE UNSUCCESSFUL, THE DECISION WAS MADE TO DISCONTINUE THE UNLOADING PROCESS.
column169: THERE WAS NO ACTION REQUIRED ON OUR PART AS THE CUSTOMER NEEDS ONLY TO REPLACE THE VALVE. A REPLACEMTN VALVE HAS BEEN ORDERED.

column168: TOBY GARTH WAS PULLING TWO 1000 GAL ANHYDROUS NURSE TANKS WITH A SINGLE AXLE INTERNATIONAL TRUCK, HEADING EAST AS HE APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION OF DIVISION AND 725 WEST (JEFFERCTION TWSP OF TIPTON COUNTY) ANOTHER MOTORIST TRAVELING WEST ON DIVISION RD. CROSSED THE CENTERLINE. TOBY EVADED THE MOTORIST AND AVOIDED A COLLISON HOWEVER THE FORCE OF THE INERTIA OF THE FULL TANKS JACK-KNIFED THE COMBINATION UNIT AND PUSHED IT INTO A NEARBY DITCH. THE OTHER MOTORIST PROPTY FLED THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT. THE FRONT TANK (14) STAYED CONNECTED TO THE TOW UNIT AND TIPPED OVER. THE BACK UNIT (12) SHEARED AT THE CENTER COUPLER OF THE RUNNING GEAR AND THE FRONT OF THE GER REMAINED ATTACHED WHILE THE BACK HALF OF THE RUNNING GEAR AND THE TANK SKIDDED ACROSS THE ROAD AND CAME TO REST ON THE NORTH SIDE OF THE DIVISION ROAD DITCH. THE DRIVE TOBY GARTH CALLED 911 REPORTING THE ACCIDENT AND REQUESTING ASSISTANCE. EMERGENCY RESPONDERS RESTRICTED THE AREA AND ENDUP EVACUATING 7 PEOPLE FROM THE IMMEDIATE SURROUNDING PROPERTIES FOR PRECAUTIONARY PURPOSES. DIVISION ROAD WAS CLOSED TO TRAFFIC AS THE REAR TANK DISCHARGED THE ANHYDROUS FROM THE DAMAGE FILL VLAVE THAT COULD NOT BE CLOSED. BOTH OF THE TANKS HAD INDIVIDUAL CAPACITIES OF 1000 GALLONS AND WERE FILLED TO 85% (APPROX. 850 GALLONS). THE REAR TANK STOPPED LEAKING AND RESPONDERS WERE ABLE TO CAP THE VALVE. BOTH TANKS RECEIVED DAMAGE THAT WILL REQUIRE THEM TO BE REMOVED FROM SERVICE. IT WAS ORIGINALLY THOUGHT THAT THE TANK HAD DISCHARGED ITS FULL CONTENTS, AND SINCE THE RUNNING GEAR WAS DAMAGED IRREPARABLY WEIGHING THE VESSEL WAS DIFFICULT BUT AFTER REVIEWING THE GAUGES OF THE TANK IT WAS DETERMINED THAT 550 GALLONS OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS DISCHARGED.
column169: THE CPS OPERATOR WAS OBSERVING ALL APPLICABLE LAWS AND UNFORTUNATELY REQUIRED TO TAKE EVASIVE ACTION AS A RESULT OF ANOTHER MOTORIST'S IRRESPONSIBLE BEHAVIOR. THE UNIT WAS TRAVELING AT THE APPROPRIATE SPEED AND WAS CORRECTLY SIZED FOR THE TRANSPORT OF THE WEIGHT INVOLVED IN THE SHIPMENT. THE DRIVER, EMERGENCY RESPONDERS, STATE AUTHORITIES AND COMPANY EMERGENCY RESPONDERS PROVIDED PROMPT AND EFFICIENT RESPONSE TO THE EMERGENCY.

column168: I WAS ON BEEPER FOR DANGEROUS GOOD ADMINISTRATION/CORPORATE SAFETY WHEN I RECEIVED A CALL FROM A CUSTOMER, PPL WHO NEEDED TO INFORM US THAT HE DISCOVERED THEY HAD OFFERED A SHIPMENT TO FEDEX EXPRESS WITHOUT PROPERLY DECLARING IT AS A DG SHIPMENT. TO THEIR KNOWLEDGE THERE WAS NO DG MARKINGS, LABELS, SHIPPER'S DECLARATION NOR AIRBILL/AUTOMATION INDICATION THAT DG WAS PRESENT. THE CUSTOMER, CHARLES PURCELL ALSO EMAILED ME THE MATERIAL SAFTETY DATA SHEET (MSDS) WHICH CLEARLY INDICATED THAT IT WAS FLAMMABLE LIQUID, NAMELY UN 1133, ADHESIVES, 3 PACKING GROUP II. I NOTIFIED OUR GLOBAL OPERATIONS CONTROL WHO WAS ABLE TO CONTACT DISPATCH AND THEN THE COURIER WHO WAS TOLD TO PULL THIS SHIPMENT WHEN HE ARRIVED AT THE NEWARK HUBAND GIVE THIS PACKAGE TO A DG SPECIALIST TO HOLD FOR FAA. FAA AGEN JUSTIN BOBKO WAS NOTIFIED VIA VOICE MAIL ON MONDAY, MAY 1ST. FEDEX HELD THE SHIPMENT PENDING HIS INVESTIGATION. PLEASE NOTE THAT FEDEX EXPRESS WAS ABLE TO PREVENT THIS SHIPMENT FROM BEING PLACED ON A FLIGHT BECAUSE THE SHIPPER/CUSTOMER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED US WHEN THEY BECAME AWARE OF THEIR MISTAKE.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00PM, CST, TRIPLE 6 DRIVER, AFTER LOADING, WAS LEAVING LEWIS CHEMICAL, 8 NORTH SYCAMORE ST., ROME, GA. THE LOADING AREA IS BETWEEN THE FACILITY WALL AND THE RAIL ROAD TRACKS. THERE IS A FOUR FOOT DITCH BETWEEN THE LOADING AREA AND THE RAILROAD TRACKS. THERE IS A CEMENT WALL EXTENDING FROM THE BUILDING APPROXIMATELY 6-7 FOOT. AT THE TIME, THERE WAS A RED PICKUP TRUCK PARKED IN FRONT OF THE WALL AND TO THE RIGHT OF THE PICKUP TRUCK WAS A SEMI-TRACTOR AT THE LEWIS CHEMICAL DOCK DOOR. THE OTHER TRACTOR/TRAILER WAS PARKED ABOUT A THIRD OF THE WAY ACROSS SYCAMORE STREET. ACROSS THE STREET FROM THE LOADING AREA IS A FENCED FACILITY. TO THE RIGHT ON SYCAMORE STREET IS A RESIDENTIAL AREA. AS THE DRIVER PULLED OUT AND ATTEMPTED TO GO LEFT ACROSS THE RAILROAD TRACKS, THE EDGE OF THE DITCH BEGAN TO CRUMBLE. DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO PULL THE TRAILER THROUGH THE COLLAPSE OF THE DITCH, BUT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER SLID TO THE BOTTOM AND THE TRAILER TURNED ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE. THE TRACTOR REMAINED HOOKED TO THE TRAILER AND DID NOT TURN OVER. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY EXITED THE VEHICLE ON THE PASSENGER SIDE AND INSPECTED THE TRAILER. HE FOUND NO PRODUCT LEAKING, BUT OBTAINED A 5 GALLON BUCKET FROM LEWIS CHEMICAL TO PUT UNDER THE VAPOR RECOVERY OUTLET. LEWIS CHECMICAL CALLED 911. ROME POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS WERE ON SCENE. GEORGIA DOT OFFICER INSPECTED DRIVER'S CDL AND PAPERWORK. FIRE COMMANDER PHIL LITTON REPORTED THAT THE BARREL WAS INTACT AND THAT THE SMALL DRIP AT THE VAPOR RECOVERY OUTLET WAS BEING CONTAINED IN A 5 GALLON BUCKET. OUR DRIVER OBTAINED A PIPE WRENCH AND RE-TIGHTENED THE VAPOR RECOVERY LINE. THE DRIP WAS SEALED AND PRODUCT CONTAINED.    COMMANDER LITTON CALLED FOR A 100-YARD EVACUATION AT THE SCENE. AT APPROXIMATELY 3:45 PM, MR. ROBERT WOOD FROM NORFOLK SOUTHERN RAILROAD, ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER, ALSO ARRIVED. AT APPROXIMATELY 6:30PM; THE FIRE AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS DEPARTED THE SCENE AND MR. WOOD WAS IN CHARGE. BRIAN WASOWICZ, PRESIDENT OF TRIPLE G ENTERPRISES, INC. WAS IN TELEPHONE CONTACT WITH MR. WOOD. THEY AGREED THAT THE TRAILER SHOULD BE UNLOADED BEFORE BEING UP RIGHTED. TRIPLE G CONTACTED ANOTHER CARRIER FROM ATLANTA WHO CAME TO THE SCENE TO TRANS LOAD THE PRODUCT. ONCE THE PRODUCT WAS OFF THE TRAILER, THE VEHICLE WAS PULLED UP OUT OF THE DITCH BY TOWING COMPANY. THROUGHOUT THIS INCIDENT, NO PRODUCT WAS RELEASED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT. ALL PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN A 5 GALLON BUCKET. ANOTHER 5 GALLON BUCKET WAS USED DURING THE TRANS LOADING PROCESS. BOTH BUCKETS OF PRODUCT WERE RETURNED TO LEWIS CHEMICAL.
column169: LEWIS CHEMICAL HAS PUT BRIGHT YELLOW POST ON THE LEFT SID THEIR DRIVEWAY PREVENTING ANYMORE DRIVERS FROM TURNING LEFT OUT OF THEIR DRIVEWAY.    MR. ROBERT WOOD HAS REPORTED THAT NORFOLK SOUTHERN IS WORKING WITH THEIR ENGINEERING DEPARTMENT REGARDING THE ELIMINATION OF THAT DITCH AT THE CROSSING.    TRIPLE G HAS RESTRICTED ALL LEFT TURNS OUT OF THE LEWIS CHECMICAL FACILITIES BY ADDING THESE INSTRUCTIONS TO OUR DRIVER DISPATCH INFORMATION. TRIPLE G IS ALSO USING THIS INCIDENT AS A TEACHING TOOL AT OUR NEXT SAFETY MEETING.

column168: ON 4/23/2013, AT 15:00, A TANK CAR WITH PHOSPHORIC ACID SOLUTION WAS BEING TRANSFERRED TO A CARGO TANK TRUCK. THE TRANSFER OPERATIONS WERE BEING CONDUCTED BY KINDER MORGAN, A CONTRACT LOADING COMPANY. THE TRANSFER WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY PRESSURING THE TANK CAR TO 40 PSIG, AND TRANSFERRING THE MATERIAL TO THE CARGO TANK VIA 3" CHEMICAL HOSE WITH CAM LOCK FITTINGS ON EACH END. APPROXIATELY 10 MINUTES AFTER THE TRANSFER BEGAN, THE CAM LOCK CONNECTION ON THE RAIL CAR BECAME DISCONNECTED. THIS RESULTED IN PHOSPHORIC ACID BEING SPRAYED OUTSIDE O THE CONTAINMENT AREA. THE TRANSFER WAS STOPPED AS SOON AS THE INCIDENT WAS NOTICED. THE INCIDENT INVESTIGATION SHOWED THAT THE CAM LOCK FITTING WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED. THE SPILL WAS SECURED AT 15:10. CLEAN UP OPERATIONS AND THE INCIDENT INVESTIGATION WERE STARTED IMMEDIATELY. THE SPILL WAS RELEASED TO LAND AND DID NOT GO OFF SITE.
column169: 1.) ALL CONTRACT LOADING EMPLOYEES ARE BEING REQUIRED TO RETAKE THE DOT TRAINING COURSE PART 174 - GENERAL REQUIREMENTS FOR LOADING AND UNLOADING TANK CARS.    2.) THE REQUIREMENTS OUTLINED IN 49 CFR SUBPART B 177.834, ATTENDANCE REQUIREMENTS DURING LOADING OPERATIONS, IS BEING REVIEWED WITH ALL CONTRACTED LOADERS.    3.) CAM LOCK INSPECTIONS ARE BEING ADDED TO THE PRE-INSPECTION CHECKLISTS.    4.) A HAZOP WILL CONDUCTED ON ALL LOADING AND UNLOADING ACTIVITIES WITHIN THE PLANT. THIS WILL BE COMPLETE BY 7/1/2013.

column168: On April 18, 2013 at approximately 11:00 a.m. central time traveling southbound on Highway 463 in truck #45, Robert Morales lost control of his tractor and trailer.  It appears that in his attempt to gain control of his vehicle and trailer, he overcorrected, sending his truck across the highway into oncoming traffic.  In doing so, his trailer looks to have jack-knifed around to the right colliding with an oncoming Ford F-250 truck and trailer.  The driver of the Ford truck was killed on impact.  Robert’s truck continued across that lane and off the road.  It appears that he attempted steering the truck back onto the highway before it came to a stop with the trailer detached and laying behind it.  Due to the impact with the other vehicle, the tank carrying 185 bbls of condensate ruptured the right side of the tanker and caused a spill of approximately 176 bbls on the road and into the embankment of the road. The condensate was release upon impact with spillage continuing for about 15 minutes following the accident.  Due to the size of the rupture, about 2 feet by 4 feet, nothing could be done to mitigate the effects of the release.
column169: While it is not known exactly how the driver lost control of the tractor and trailer, we have had a safety meeting since then with current driver stressing the importance of always maintaining control of your vehicle no matter what weather conditions they might face.  Drivers have been reminded to drive defensively and to show caution with respect to speed when adverse weather conditions are present.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Leak was discovered at rear of trailer.  Trailer was isolated and MSDS was consulted.  Seymours Spill Response of Commerce, Georgia was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon inspection of the trailer, one (1) 55-gallon drum of printing ink was discovered with a crease at bottom.  The entire contents had released inside the trailer.  Seymours Spill Response utilized absorbent material to clean the trailer floor and wiped down all contaminated freight.  Damaged drum was overpacked along with spent absorbent material and cleanup debris.  One (1) drum of waste was held at Ssymours Spill Response, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Wilson Trucking Corporation will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: NATX 364248 was found in the overload track by a contractor with product running down both side of the car.  The car was in hold status due to being overloaded.  The car was assessed and determined to be leaking from the vapor valve where it connects to the male pipe thread.  The customer was contacted and a vacuum truck was utilized to reduce the car and the leak stopped.  Once the car was reduced the vapor valve was assessed again and determined to be cross threaded, removed, and reapplied.  The car was wiped clean and held for an OTMA-2 applied for by the shipper.

column168: DRIVER ENCOUNTERED HIGH WINDS AS HE WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON I-40 WEST OF LITTLE ROCK, AR. THE HIGH WINDS CONTINUED FOR THE NEXT 900 MILES. THE DRIVER STOPPED APPROXIMATELY EVERY HOUR TO CHECK THE LOAD, TIE DOWNS AND TIGHTEN THE TARP STRAPS. THE TARP AND THE TARP STRAPS WERE FLAPPING AGAINST THE TOTE. ONE TOTE WAS GOUGED BY THE TARP STRAP. THE DAMAGED TOTE WAS LOCATED ON THE DRIVER SIDE OF THE TRAILER APPROXIMATELY 12" FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THE HOLE WAS LESS THAN 1/8". SEE ATTACHED LOADING DIAGRAM AND PICTURES.  AS THE DRIVER WAS INSPECTING HIS LOAD AT THE PETRO TRUCK STOPPING CENTER, HE LIFTED THE TARP AND SAW A DROP OF LIQUID ON THE ALUMINUM FLOOR OF THE FLATBED. HE FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK; THE MATERIAL WAS COMING FROM A HOLE IN THE TOTE. THE DRIVER CONTACTED THE SHIPPER IMMEDIATELY. THE SHIPPER INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO PLACE ABSORBENT MATERIAL ON THE TRAILER DECK UNDER THE LEAK, OVER THE HOLE AND STAINED AREA, REPLACE THE TARP, SECURE THE AREA, DO NOT MOVE THE TRAILER AND AWAIT FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS. TWO HOURS LATER, THE SHIPPER CALLED THE DRIVER WITH ADDITIONAL INSTRUCTIONS: COVER THE HOLE WITH DUCT TAPE, STAYING 3" TO 6" AWAY AND REPLACE THE TARP. THE DRIVER PERFORMED ALL THE SHIPPERS' INSTRUCTIONS AND STAYED WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS LOCATED AWAY FROM THE OTHER VEHICLES IN THE PARKING LOT.  AN ENERGYSOLUTIONS WASTE BROKER AND HEALTH PHYSICS SPECIALIST WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO INSPECT THE GOUGE, PERFORM RADIATION SURVEYS AND REPAIR THE PACKAGE FOR DELIVERY TO ENERGYSOLUTIONS IN CLIVE, UTAH.  NO ELEVATED RADIATION READINGS OR CONTAMINATION WERE DETECTED. SEE THE ATTACHED REPORT FROM THE AZ RADIATION REGULATORY AGENCY.

column168: Tank car OPIX 383 was reported venting a mixture of nitrogen and commodity in the railyard. OPIX 383 was cordoned off in the railyard. Local F.D. on scene requested that yard operations cease. Responder's inspection of OPIX 383 revealed a steady hiss emanating from OPIX 383's 75 psi pressure relief device (PRD). Responder's replaced the PRD's O-rings which ended the PRD vent by 2126 hrs. CDT, 4/19/2013. Yard operations were resumed by 2240 hrs. CDT, 4/19/2013. Afterwards, responders added nitrogen into OPIX 383 to replenish the dry nitrogen pad within OPIX 383.

column168: CHEMTREC notified BNSF of a citizen's report concerning a liquid leaking tank car entrained in a BNSF train in Columbus, MS. Leaking tank car was identified as UTLX 208526 which was currently staged and parked in a rail siding. By 1345 hrs. CDT, 4/17/2013, local F.D./county HazMat repsonders were able to stop the commodity release from UTLX 208526 by securing the camlock cap closure on the liquid line that was found not completely clamped or locked down. Afterwards, contract responders fully closed the liquid line valve and ensured that the camlock closure cap was properly secured. Responders used absorbent padding and applied 'Oil Gator' absorbent to all observed ground spillage which was estimated at 100 gallons or less. A degreaser solution was applied to the spillage on UTLX 208526 and four additional rail cars that incurred commodity spray from UTLX 208526's release. These five rail cars were then pressure washed. Spent cleaning liquids were captured atop protective poly sheeting. An application of Micro-Blaze was also used on ground spillage areas. Spent cleaning materials and the poly sheeting were collected and earmarked for appropriate disposal.  Outage measurement of remaining commodity within UTLX 208526 versus commodity loading calculations indicated a differential of 4381 gallons of commodity possibly lost in transit.

column168: On April 24th, 2013 at 0626 hours, Frontier Yard Car Department personnel discovered SHPX 222333, a loaded tank car of Petroleum Crude Oil to have oil residue on the sides and dripping off the bottom of the tank car. The tank car was isolated and CHEMTREC was notifed, report 2013-04-24-00045. Mr. Alex MaCleod from Irving Oil Terminals, LLC, 506-343-1699, Shipper Mr. Chris Lewis, from Bakken Oil Express, LLC, 701-690-4742  were notified. EP+S of Vermont, Inc. a CSX Emergency Response contractor was notified to respond and found the sample line valve open one turn and the securement plug not installed. The valve was closed, the plug was installed and tool tightened. SHPX 222333 was wiped down and released for disposition.    An AAR 7.1 report is not required.  No Special Switching Movement was completed.       NARRI Index Cause Code - 513 = 5 pts.  5x(5+3+1)x(2+0) = 80
column169: Mr. Chris Lewis of Bakken Oil Express, LLC will have a safety stand-down, to discuss proper securement of tank cars prior to release and inspection, after loading the petroleum crude oil product.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While traveling on Interstate 88 near mile marker 102, the tractor-tanker unit was involved in a vehicle accident.  Apparently in an effort to avoid a third party vehicle, the tractor-tanker unit rolled-over into the center median.  As a result approximately 20 gallons of ethanol released.  The spill was terminated by response personnel on site and Breckenridge Trucking, Inc. utilized its own resources to pump off and recover the ethanol without further incident.  No additional cleanup was required.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and was the result of a vehicle accident, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Breckenridge Trucking, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Driver was pumping from the inground tank at the station into a compartment of the trailer to tranfer the product to a different location.  The driver verified the amount in the inground tank with the veeder root reading and the product would fit into the compartment of the trailer accourding to the reading.  The driver failed to realize that the inground tank was manifolded with another tank and that the manifold was not closed.  The product from the manifolded tank flowed over into the tank that the driver was empting and over filled the compartment of the trailer by approx. 50 gallons of kerosene.  The product ran down the trailer and only impacted asphalt.  The driver immediately stopped the flow of product and accessed his spill kit and started to contain the spill.  SET Environmental was called and responded to the spill for remediation.
column169: Our safety manager spoke to the driver and relayed the importance of verifing all tanks when doing a pump out.  We also addressed the issue with the customer impacted and asked that their safety team review thier in house procedures for pump outs proformed at thier locations regarding manifolded tanks.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Tank car UTLX 201731 was reported leaking commodity from one of its two 75 psi pressure relief devices (PRD) during movement from the railyard's repair track after completion of hand brake related repairs. Movement was stopped and UTLX 201731, deemed safe to move, was isolated in the railyard. No commodity release was observed when UTLX 201731 remained motionless. The local loader of UTLX 201731 was notified and arranged to have UTLX 201731 unloaded on 5/04/2013 without further incident. The A-end PRD spring assembly was reported observed at the bottom of the tank after the commodity transfer process was completed. A broken PRD stem was suspected as the cause of the PRD failure. Spillage on the shell of UTLX 201731 was cleaned and no ground impact from spillage was reported. UTLX 201731 is being held for FRA OTMA approval to direct tank car to a qualified repair facility.

column168: The driver of the TransVac vehicle, Mr.Speer was traveling north bound on US HWY 79. Mr. Speer failed to maintain control of the tractor/van trailer and ran off the right side of the roadway into the North Bound ditch. The tractor/van trailer traveled in the ditch approximately 154 feet and struck the edge of the culvert of a bridge. Tractor/van trailer came to a final rest in the North Bound ditch facing in a northern direction. The van trailer was transporting 20 Super Sacks of Flame Retardant. The retardant was spilled in the accident thru the front of the van from the impact of the sudden stop. The office of Emergency Services was notified and responded to the scene. Allied International Emergency LLC Services responded to the scene and was responsible for the clean up of the spill.  Note: Mr Speer stated that something broke on the tractor prior to the accident that was hendering him from steering the truck. Till this date we have not been able to determine any substantial evidence that would prove any mechanical failure.
column169: TransVac went back and investigated the previous vehicle inspections reports (noted no defects) and recommended that the drivers conduct a thorough inspestion, possbily catching or identifying any mechanical failure, if this was the actual fault of the accident. Taking appropriate action(s) at the present time of the inspection.

DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE WAS APPROACHING A LEFT TURN ONTO SAN DIEGO MISSION RD. THE ROAD WAS ON A DOWN-HILL PLANE CAUSING AN OFF-CAMBER EFFECT WHILE TURNING. THE ACCIDENT WAS FURTHER EXACERBATED BY THE FACT THAT THE DRIVER WAS TRYING TO MAKE THE TURN BEFORE THE LIGHT TURNED RED WHICH LED TO HIM GOING INTO THE TURN TOO FAST FOR THE ROAD AND VEHICLE SAFETY CONDITIONS. AS THE DRIVER COMPLETED THE TURN ONTO SAN DIEGO MISSION RD., THE LOAD IN THE TANK VEHICLE SHIFTED BECAUSE OF THE SPEED AT WHICH THE TURN WAS EXECUTED CAUSING THE ROLL-OVER.    EMERGENCY PERSONNEL WERE CALLED BY THE DRIVER AFTER HE EXTRICATED HIMSELF FROM THE WRECKED VEHICLE. SD FIRE DEPARTMENT SET UP DAMS TO CONTROL THE SPREAD OF PRODUCT THAT WAS LEAKING ROM THE TRAILER DUE TO THE ACCIDENT. SD FIRE SET UP A QUARANTINE AREA AROUND THE ACCIDENT SCENE AND ONLY FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL WERE ALLOWED INTO THE ACCIDENT SCENE FOR APPROXIMATELY 8 HOURS AFTER THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT. NRC ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES INC. (REMEDIATION COMPANY HIRED BY APEX FOR CLEN-UP EFFORTS) WAS ALLOWED IN AT APPROXIMATELY 4AM TO PUMP OFF THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE TANK VEHICLE AND TO START VACUUMING UP PRODUCT THAT HAD LEAKED OUT.
column169: SPECIFIC TRAINING FOR ROLL-OVER ACCIDENTS IS PROVIDED TO EACH HAZ-MAT CDL DRIVER DURING ORIENTATION. MR. LUCAS HAD GONE THROUGH THIS TRAINING LESS THAN 60 DAYS PRIOR TO THE ACCIDENT.    AFTER THE ACCIDENT, A SAFETY MEETING WAS HELD WITH ALL DRIVERS (NOT INCLUDING MR. LUCAS AS HE IS OUT ON WORKER'S COMP) TO READDRESS THIS ISSUE AND RE-STRESS THE IMPORTANCE OF THE SPEED-ADAPTATION PHENOMENON AND LOOKING AT YOUR SPEEDOMETER BEFORE ENTERING A CURVE OR TURN. ALSO STRESSED WAS THE IMPORTANCE OF NOT TRYING TO BEAT TRAFFIC LIGHTS WHEN PERFORMING THEIR NORMAL DUTIES.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, TYPE A PACKAGE NON-SPECIAL FORM, NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY  0705 ON APRIL 26, 2013 A CARDINAL HEALTH NUCLEAR PHARMACY SERVICES VEHICLE LOST CONTROL 3.1 MILES EAST OF US-49 ON MS-8. THE VEHICLE WENT OFF OF THE ROADWAY TO THE RIGHT, CAME BACK ONTO THE HIGHWAY, AND THEN OVERTURNED COMING TO REST WHEELS DOWN TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD. THE VEHICAL INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT WAS A 2009 FORD RANGER CARRYING CLASS 7 RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL USED FOR RADIOPHARMACEUTICALS. THE FIRST RESPONDERS ON THE SCENE ATTENDED TO THE DRIVER WHO WAS EJECTED FROM THE VEHICLE. WHILE THE VEHICLE WAS OVERTURNING THE TRUCK BED COVER WAS TORN OFF THE VEHICLE. THIS CAUSED ONE RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL PACKAGE FROM THE BED OF THE VEHICLE TO BE EJECTED FROM ITS BLOCKING AND BRACING. THE FIRST RESPONDERS ATTENDING TO THE SCENE PICKED UP THE PACKAGE AND PLACED IT IN THE BED OF THE VEHICLE. THIS INCIDENT CAUSED THE HIGHWAY TO BE CLOSED IN BOTH DIRECTIONS FOR APPROXIMATELY 3.5 HOURS. IN TOTAL THERE WERE FIVE (5) PACKAGES IN THE VEHICLE. OF THE FIVE (5) PACKAGES, THREE (3) WERE LIMITED QUANTITY AND THE REMAINING TWO (2) WERE WHITE 1. THE TWO (2) PACKAGES THAT WERE EJECTED FROM THE VEHICLE WERE INTACT AND NO RELEASE OF MATERIAL OCCURRED. THE TOTAL ACTIVITY FOR BOTH PACKAGES WAS 208.5405 MCI OF TC-99M AND 115.7297 MCI OF TI-201. A CARDINAL HEALTH REPRESENTATIVE WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO CHECK FOR SUSPECTED CONTAMINATION. CONTAMINATION WIPES AND SURVEYS WERE TAKEN OF THE VEHICLE, PACKAGES, AND ACCIDENT SCENE. ALL READINGS INDICATED NO CONTAMINATION. THE PACKAGES WERE TAKEN BACK TO THE FACILITY BY THE CARDINAL HEALTH REPRESENTATIVE AND THE VEHICLE WAS TOWED.
column169: THIS INCIDENT IS CURRENTLY UNDER REVIEW.

column167: Other-EAST PENN IS OWNER OF CA
column168: On 4/17/2013 at around 0802 a Holderfield Battery Truck was headed east bound on County Park Road. The driver stated he saw another vehicle coming toward him and started to ease over to the right to ensure enough room to pass. As he was pulling to the right, he rubbed the guard rail and then dropped off the shoulder. He tried to correct and get back on the road but could not. The truck struck a few guard rails and a Utility pole and then rolled coming to rest on the passenger side. The utility lines were live and still on the vehicle. The driver had to be extricated by the Paducah Fire once the lines were disconnected by Paducah Power. Driver was taken to the local hospital for checking. KY Commercial Vehicle Enforcement also responded to the scene.  The contents of 356 batteries spilled out of the box truck.  A call was made back to main headquarters, East Penn Manufacturing Co., Lyons Station, PA for further help on clean up. An Environmental Contractor was called to the scene for clean  up. The National Response Center was notified a long with the Kentucky DEP. By the time the Environmental contractor got to the scene the wrecker service had begun off-loading the batteries from the box truck. The Environmental Contractor indicated that there were engine oils that also released due to the incident.   East Penn Mfg was working on getting a replacement truck to reload the batteries since the box truck was completely damaged and the cargo could not be reloaded back onto the original box truck. Holderfield Battery was also sending help to determine the status of the batteries.  The leaking batteries were placed into individual poly bags and repalletized. The "good' batteries will need to be wiped down due to the acid that spilled on them.  A neutralizing solution  was made to apply to the released battery acid.  The box truck was uprighted  and the Environmental Contractor neutralized the released acid that was visible on the truck and the surrounding area. The Consignee of the load sent a truck to reload the batteries.  The batteries will be stationed at the consignee overnight for Holder field employees to go through them to determine which ones are OK for sale and which ones will be sold as seconds and which ones will go back to East Penn Mfg for proper disposal at their secondary lead smelter.  After all the batteries were repalletized and reloaded the Environmental Contractor continued the clean up of the diesel fuel/engine oil.  Drums of hazardous waste were created.  One drum contained diesel fuel, antifreeze and motor oil debris.  the other drums contained cleaned up battery acid contaminated material. The Environmental Contractor will take care of proper testing of the drums for proper disposal.
column169: EAST PENN DOES NOT HAVE ANY SUGGESTIONS OR CHANGES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. THE BATTERIES WERE CORRECTLY WRAPPED TO THE SKIDS AND THE LOAD LOCKS WERE CORRECTLY INSTALLED. THE SKIDS WERE LOADED PROPERLY TO DISTRIBUTE THE WEIGHT ON THE TRUCK. THE INCIDENT WAS THE DRIVERS JUDGEMENT ERROR.

column168: April 18, 2013: During a routine inspection at Conrail's Pavonia Yard, Camden, NJ, FRA Hazardous Materials Inspector R. Dedow noted various areas on the manway nozzle of tank car CTCX 733469, load Petroleum Crude Oil, to be stained.  Further inspection with Conrail's A. Richter, RIsk Management, confirmed same.  Manway cover securement bolts appeared to be tool tight.    Shipper, Eighty-Eight Oil LLC, contracted with emergency response contractor Hepaco-React to correct and remediate the car.  Hepaco-React's inspection included loosening the manway cover securement bolts and opening the manway cover.  Noted the manway cover gasket noted with large/deep grooves in various areas of the gasket.  One of the manway cover securement bolt washers was cupped, possibly due to force associated with use of a pneumatic tool to tighten the manway cover securement bolts.  It was determined that the cupped washer caused it to hang up in the bolt's threads, whereby prohibiting the securement nut from being adequately secured.    Manway nozzle was wiped clean and manway cover was resecured tool tight by use of wrench.  Car okayed to be forwarded to original destination for unloading, and further repair/replacement of washer and gasket.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: DRIVER FAILED TO DISCONNECT LOADING ARM FROM TRAILER, AS DRIVER MOVED POWER UNIT HE NOTICED LOADING ARM WAS STILL CONNECTED TO TRAILER, HE IMMEDIATELY STOPPED WHEN HE NOTICED THAT LOADING ARM WAS STILL CONNECTED, BUT NOT IN TIME, THEREFORE CAUSING A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 70 GALLONS, THE RELEASE LASTED AN ESTIMATED TIME OF 3 MIN. THE ONLY DAMAGE DONE WAS AN ALUMINUM FLANGE CONNECTED TO THE TRAILER, FLANGE WAS REPLACED, THERE WAS NO DAMAGE DONE TO THE SHIPPERS LOADING ARM. EVERYTHING WAS CONTAINED IN THE PREMISES, NOTHING WAS EXPOSED, IT WAS CLEANED UP BY IN HOUSE PERSONNEL.
column169: IMMEDIATELY AFTER INCIDENT OCCURRENCE DRIVER DELIVER THE LOAD AND RETURNED TO THE TRUCK YARD. AFTER RIO EXPRESS SEND DRIVER FOR A POST ACCIDENT DRUG TEST, WHICH CAME BACK NEGATIVE. RIO HAD A MEETING WITH DRIVER DISCUSSING INCIDENT AND DISCUSSING CONSEQUENCES OF SPILL, DRIVER ACKNOWKEDGED THAT IT WAS JUST HUMAN ERROR, HE FAILED TO DISCONNECT LOADING ARM, THERFORE CAUSING INCIDENT, DRIVER ACKNOWLEDGE THAT HE WOULD BE MORE CAUTIOUS AND DOUBLE CHECK EVERY PROCEDURE TO VERIFY THAT EVERY VALVE IS CLOSED AND DISCONNECTED BEFORE MOVING VEHICLE.

DRIVER MOVED TRUCK TO ROAD AND GAVE INFORMATION AND WAS THEN TOLD HE COULD LEAVE. A HAZMAT TEAM (SOUTHLAND RESPONSE) ARRIVED AND CONTACTED ME ABOUT PRODUCT ON PARKING LOT, IN BACK YARD AND POOLING AT THE EDGE OF THE STREET. MAINTAINENCE MEN WERE DISPATCHED TO APPLY ABSORB ALL. HAZMAT HELD OFF CLEAN UP UNTIL MY ARRIVALL AT SITE. TCEQ (BEAUMONT DIVISION CALLED AND SAID AN INSPECTOR WAS DISPATCHED AND WOULD ARRIVE IN ABOUT 2-2.5 HRS.    WHEN ON SITE I WAS MET BY EDDIE FLEMMONS WITH SOUTHLAND WHO BEGAN TELLING ME WE NEEDED TO START RIPPING UP THE PARKING LOT, REMOVE ASPHALT AND REMEDIATE THE SITUATION. RICHARD SAMMONS, FRANK GREEN, RANDY BOYLE, LESTER GLAZE AND MICHAEL ALLEN WERE ALL ON SITE ALONG WITH ME, DENISE WILLIAMS AND NORMA. WE ALL DISCUSSED THE ISSUE AND TRIED TO FIGURE OUT WHAT HAPPENED. SINCE THIS LOCATION IS CURRENTLY UNDER REMEDIATION BY CARDNO ATC I NOTIFIED THEM AND THEY DISPATCHED MATT TO SITE. I ALSO MENTIONED THAT TCEQ HAD BEEN CONTACTED AND WAS DISPATCHING AN INSPECTOR. TO KEEP MIGRATION MINIMAL, OUR MAINTENENCE GUYS PLACE ABOUT 5-6 BAGS OF ABSORB-ALL ONTO THE PARKING LOT. IT WAS DECIDED TO WAIT FOR TCEQ AND FOLLOW INSTRUCTIONS FOR CLEAN UP. WHEN TCEQ ARRIVED, SOUTHLAND WAS ASKED TO LEAVE AND TOLD THE SITE WAS NOW BEING HANDLED THROUGH ARDNO.    JODI PATTERSON ARRIVED ON SITE AND SPOKE TO FRANK GREEN ABOUT THE EVENTS. SHE ASKED FOR THREE MONTHS INVENTORY CONTROL, THE MANIFEST TICKET AND BILL OF LADING WHICH EVERYTHING WAS PROVIDED AT SITE EXCEPT FOR THE INVENTORY CONTROL AND SHE ASKED ME TO EMAIL OR FAX. WE DISCUSSED THREE WAYS THIS SPILL COULD HAVE HAPPENED: VENT LINES COULD HAVE BEEN STOPPED UP, FLAPPER ON THE OVERFILL DID NOT FUNCTION PROPERLY OR BY DRIVER MISTAKE. FRANK ELIMINATED THE VENT LINES BY BLOWING AIR THROUGH THEM WITH AIR HOSE. JODIE ASKED FOR ESTIMATED GALLONS LOST AND FRANK REPLIED ABOUT 20-50 GALLONS. SHE ASKED WHO WOULD BE DOING SOIL SAMPLES AND I TOLD HER CARDNO WAS IN ROUTE. SHE ASKED THAT WHEN TESTING WAS COMPLETED THE RESULTS BE SENT TO HER. SHE LEFT AND MATT ARRIVED ABOUT 2:30. SOIL SAMPLING BEGAN ABOUT 3. ONCE HOLES WERE DRILLED, THE ASPHALT WAS ABOUT 6 INCHES THICK BEFORE SOIL BEGAN. AROUND 8 SAMPLES WERE TAKEN 15 FEET APART STARTING FROM EDGE OF STREET TO TANK HOLD AREA. OUT OF THE 8 TAKEN, ONE SAMPLE NEXT TO TANK HOLD GAVE OFF A HIGH LEVEL. MATT TALKED WITH JODI AND SHE ASKED THAT HE PUT RESULTS IN AN RDR AND SEND TO HER FOR REVIEW.    SINCE THIS SITE IS IN REMEDIATION FOR HIGH ACTION LEVELS OVER THE TANK HOLD, MATT FEELS THIS SPILL WILL NOT HINDER CLOSURE OF THE LPST AND THAT THE SPILL WILL BE DOCUMENTED AS A SEPERATE EVENT AND CLOSED OUT. WE CAN ONLY WAIT TO HEAR COMMENTS FROM TCEQ.

column168: The tractor-trailer operated by Pope Transport Company was travelling Eastbound on I-26. The tractor-trailer approached a vehicle travelling below the speed limit and collided with the vehicle. After the collision, the tractor-trailer left the roadway to the right and overturned. The tank trailer disconnected from the tractor. The shell of the tank trailer was punctured, resulting in the release of petroleum product to the environment. Based on observed damage to the tank trailer, the estimated duration of the release was approximately 20 minutes. The interstate highway (I-26) was closed for approximately 12 hours. Upon being notified of the incident, Pope Transport Company management contacted Highlands Environmental Solutions, Inc. (HES) for emergency spill response and remediation services. Personnel from HES and a subcontractor responded to the scene on the date of the incident. The vehicle wreckage was removed, and pooled petroleum product was recovered. Environmental remediation activities began within two days of the date of the incident, after permission to proceed was received from the South Carolina Department of Transportation. Site remediation activities included: Recovery and removal of pooled petroleum product, removal of petroleum-impacted vegetation, removal of petroleum-impacted soil, and backfill/restoration of the excavated area. Environmental remediation activities were completed within two weeks of the date of the incident.

PRELIMINARY REPORTS INDICATED PUNCTURE TO A TOTE FROM A BROKEN PALLET. AT 9:27A.M. WE CONTACTED THE MISSOURI DIVISION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND GIVEN REPORT GENERATOR #130422-0929-KAH. FINAL REPORTS ARE NOT COMPLETE AS OF THIS DATE AND WE ARE WAITING ENVIROMENTAL SERVICES FOR FINAL REPORT.
column169: BASED ON PRELIMINARY REPORTS, THE APPARENT CAUSE WAS PRODUCTS USED TO SECURE FREIGHT FROM MOVING AND/OR SHIFTING. WE'VE BEEN IN CONTACT WIHT THE SHIPPER REGARDING THE INCIDENT AND WE ARE AWAITING THE FINAL REPORT FROM ENVIROMENTAL SERVICES IN ORDER TO REVIEW WHERE IMPROVEMENTS CAN BE MADE TO PREVENT FURTHER RECURRENCE.

column168: 1. THE OPERATOR TERRY PETERSON IS A VETERAN OF PUTTING ON NH3. HE BEEN APPLYING NH3 FOR OVER 25 YEARS WITH A VERY CLEAN SAFETY RECORD. HE WAS DRIVING OUR JD TRACTOR AND TOOLBAR AND PULLING A TWIN 1000 GALLON TANK. IT WAS EARLY AFTERNOON ON TUESDAY THE 30TH OF APRIL. TERRY WAS DRIVING WEST ON CTY RD 3 AND PROCEEDED SOUTH ON 3. AS HE WAS DRIVING STRAIGHT AHEAD ON 3 ABOUT 19MPH HE WENT ABOUT A 1/4 TO A 1/3 OF A MILE AND LOOKING STRAIGHT AHEAD. ALL OF A SUDDEN HE LOOKED IN THE MIRROR AND THE TANK WAS ALREADY PARTIALLY IN THE DITCH, AND THE WHEEL BASE OF THE TANK IS NARROWER THAN BOTH THE TOOLBAR AND THE TRACTOR. AS THE TANK WENT INTO THE DITCH ON THE WEST SIDE OF THE ROAD, THE END OF THE TANK'S HITCH WHERE THE PIN GOES IN BROKE OFF (WHERE THE TWO PIECES OF METAL CONNECT TO THE TONGUE), AND THE TANK THEN ROLLED OVER ONTO ITS TOP UPSIDE DOWN. HE THEN DROVE ABOUT 100 FEET AND PULLED OVER. HE CALLED FARM COUNTRY COOP'S OFFICE IN PINE ISLAND TO INFORM US OF THE PROBLEM. HE THEN WALKED BACK TO THE TANK AND IT WAS LEAKING. THERE WAS A SMALL CLOUD OF GAS, SO TERRY KNEW IT WAS LEAKING A LITTLE. THE WIND WAS 15 MPH OUT OF THE WEST BLOWING THE GAS OVER THE ROAD AND AWAY FROM THE TANK. 911 WAS CALLED IMMEDIATELY. A WOMAN WHO LIVED IN THE HOUSE LOCATED 60-70 YARDS AWAY ALSO ON THE WEST SIDE OF THE ROAD CAME OUT TO SEE WHATS GOING ON. TERRY TOLD HER THAT HER AND HER HUSBAND SHOULD LEAVE THE SCENE AS A PRECAUTION. THE  POLICE WERE THERE WITHIN 15 MINUTES, AND FIVE MINUTES LATER THE BRYON FIRE DEPARTMENT VOLUNTEERS WERE ON THE SCENE. THE POLICE OFFICER ON THE SCENE SAID THAT NO TICKETS WOULD BE ISSUED. THE WITNESS BEHIND THE UNIT THOUGHT THE TANK WAS TRAVELLING STRAIGHT AND NORMAL.  2. THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT/RELEASE IS STILL UNCLEAR, BUT WHAT WE KNOW IS THIS. THE SHOULDERS OF  THE BLACKTOP ROAD ARE SOFT, AND ALSO NARROW. THE ROAD IS ITSELF JUST A TWO LANE, AND WE NORMALLY HAVE TO RUN THE SHOULDER TO FIT DOWN THE ROAD. THE TANK'S TIRES ALWAYS END UP ON THE SHOULDER AT TIMES, AND IN THIS INSTANCE BECAUSE THE SHOULDER WAS NARROW AT ONLY 2 FEET OF WIDTH, THE TANK'S TIRES CAUGHT THE EDGE OF THE SHOULDER AND TERRY MAY HAVE COMPENSATED TO GET TOWARDS THE CENTER ROAD. THE TWO PIECES OF METAL WITH THE HOLES IN THEM ON THE END OF THE TONGUE WERE FINE, BUT WHERE THEY ATTACH TO THE TONGUE IS WHERE IT BROKE OFF. LOOKING AT THE METAL WHERE THEY BROKE IT LOOKS LIKE THERE WAS NOT 100% GOOD METAL LEFT. THE CONNECTION HAD A POSSIBLE WEAK AREA IN IT. THIS WOULD BE IMPOSSIBLE TO NOTICE UNLESS IT BROKE. NOW IF YOU CONSIDER THE STEEPNESS OF THE AREA, IT MAY OR MAY NOT HAVE BEEN A FACTOR. THE ONE ROLL CAGE DID ITS JOB ON ONE TANK PREVENTING THE VALVES FROM BUSTING OFF, BUT ON THE OTHER TANK THE CAGE BROKE OFF AND THE FRONT VALVE DID BREAK OFF. THE INSIDE PORTION OF THE VALVE SLAMMED SHUT BUT DID ALLOW SOME PRODUCT TO GET BY. IT DID ITS JOB MOSTLY.  3. THE IMPACT TO THE GENERAL PUBLIC WAS VERY MINIMAL. THERE WERE NO HEALTH ISSUES AT ALL. ALL PEOPLE AT THE SCENE WERE INFORMED OF THE ANHY
column169: PLEASE SEE ATTACHED ORDER TO COMPLY. WE WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT OUR TANKS THROUGHLY AND ALSO TRAIN OUR EMPLOYEES TO CONTINUE BEING CAREFUL WHEN TRANSPORTING NH3. THIS WAS TERRY'S FIRST INCIDENT AND HE WASN'T GOING THAT FAST BUT SOMEHOW CAUGHT THE SHOULDER TOO MUCH.

column168: BRANDON EATON WAS DRIVING NORTH ON CHERRY ST ROAD TRANSPORTING 2 FULL NH3 TANKS. THE RIGHT REAR WHEEL BEARING FAILED ON THE REAR TANK CAUSING THE TIRE AND RIM TO COME OFF. THE TANKS WHIPPED AS BRANDON SLOWED. THE FRONT TANK WAS PUSHED OVER ON TO THE PAVEMENT BREAKING A FILL VALVE OFF. UNION COUNTY EMERGENCY PERSONNEL AS WELL AS CPS EMPLOYEES RESPONDED. CHERRY ST WAS BLOCKED OFF IN BOTH DIRECTIONS AS THE TANK BLED OFF. AFTER TANK BLED OFF TO BELOW VALVE, THE TANK WAS LIFTED UPRIGHT AND PULLED INTO AN ADJACENT FIELD WHERE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO AN EMPTY TANK. THE ENTIRE PROCESS TOOK APPROX. 2 HRS.
column169: HOLD SAFETY MEETING WITH EMPLOYEES STRESSING IMPORTANCE OF EQUIPMENT MAINTENANCE AND SAFE DRIVING. MAKE SURE EQUIPMENT MAINTENANCE FILES FOR YEARLY EQUIPMENT INSPECTION AND 5 YR. PRESSURE CHECKS ARE CURRENT. SENT 2 ADDITIONAL EMPLOYEES TO ASMARK AMMONIA TECH TRAINING.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., AT OR ABOVE 100 C AND BELOW ITS FLASH POINT (INCLUDING MOLTEN METALS, MOLTEN SALTS, ETC.)
column168: FRA Inspector Rowan notified shipper of the car leaking vapors from the operating rod of the top operated bottom outlet valve. Shipper notified NS and responded to correct the leak.  Shipper found vapor and moisture leaking from the packing gland around the top operated bottom outlet valve rod.  Shipper tightened the packing nut and release was stopped.      The shipper told the local supervision that since this was an elevated temperature material, the heat had caused water in the car and material to expand and be released through the packing.  Since they were told it was only water vapor, NS local supervision did not think an internal NS 2090 Spill Report or 5800 report was required.      This report is being filed late because NS was not aware of this release until notified by FRA last week.
column169: No additional comments.
